english:
  title: Record of the New Tower at Lingguang
  author: Lee Saek
  language: eng
  text: |-
    When Lord Shin took up his post as magistrate of Lingguang, he swept away corruption and guided the people toward harmony. With his administrative duties in order, he cast his eyes upon the government buildings and noticed the lack of a tower.

    "Indeed," he said, "a tower exists not merely for show, but to dispel the gloom that settles in the heart and refresh the spirit—a gift of great worth to any people. How much more so for one like myself, who must receive royal envoys on behalf of the king? These messengers arrive burdened with urgent affairs, their minds always hurried, yearning for but a moment's respite. If our county cannot offer them solace, and lacks even a tower where they might find it, how can we restore their weary spirits? I fear we fail in our duty to honor those who serve the throne. Fathers and elders of this place—let us build this tower together."

    At his words, the people rushed forth with eager hands, gathering timber and organizing the work. Within ten months, a magnificent structure rose—the pride of the entire county. Truly, Lord Shin possessed the ability to transform vision into reality.

    Is it mere chance that Lingguang found such a magistrate, and that he raised this new tower now rather than in ages past? I think not. Here, green bamboo and fragrant lotus frame distant hills and the breath of the sea. Water murmurs softly through it all. Those who ascend this tower forget the burdens of their labors, and without that gentle sound of flowing water, could they ever know such grace?

    My colleague Kwon Gilbu, speaking on behalf of Lord Shin, asked me to compose this record. Though I agreed, time escaped me until my return to pay respects to my parents, when his urgent summons compelled me to write these words hastily, paying no mind to their roughness.

    I offer this only to those who serve as royal envoys: Do not think merely, "I am the king's messenger—who dares slight me?" Rather, eschew idle pleasures and base desires. Show respect for those who labor to govern this land. This is enough.

    Written in the fourth month of the year Yisi of Zhizheng.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: Royal envoys (王人) were officials dispatched from the capital to inspect provincial governance and deliver royal directives—a dignified but exhausting responsibility.
  - key: ''
    value: The year Yisi of Zhizheng corresponds to 1365 in the Gregorian calendar, during the Yuan Dynasty's final years.
